# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deployment-strategies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment contrasts with *continuous delivery* (also abbreviated CD), a similar approach in which software functionalities are also frequently delivered and deemed to be potentially capable of being deployed, but are actually not deployed.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] As such, continuous deployment can be viewed as a more complete form of automation than continuous delivery.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment has been adopted by software companies such as Meta, Microsoft, Atlassian, IBM, Adobe, and Tesla.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment extends the principles of continuous integration and delivery by including fully automated production deployment without the need for manual approval, instead relying on rigorous automated testing.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Reviews may still take place in the form developer-developer code reviews, but the need for intermediary reviewers such as a change-advisory board is minimized.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Because code changes are deployed automatically, continuous deployment requires a much higher standard of automated testing, as test quality determines the reliability of releases.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Without this, the risk of introducing production failures outweighs the benefits of deployment automation.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] In addition, continuous deployment emphasizes small incremental changes and dark launches through the use of feature toggles.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Developers can deploy code into production months before a public release by gradually adding functionality in small chunks, verifying stability, and then enabling the feature for users when it is considered ready.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment removes the need to wait for releases, as once a change passes internal testing it is automatically deployed to production.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] This allows for shorter time-to-market and more frequent releases, which in turn increases customer satisfaction and provides companies with more marketing opportunities.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] A major motivation for continuous deployment is that deploying software into the field more often makes it easier to find, catch, and fix bugs.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Deploying small, incremental changes makes it easier to trace the origin of bugs, since issues will be isolated to a recent and relatively small code change.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Under this methodology, new software features can be released to customers more quickly and frequently after their development, accelerating the delivery of value to customers and enhancing customer satisfaction.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Teams can begin to collect customer feedback almost immediately, driving rapid innovation of relevant features.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Continuous delivery requires a significant investment in adequate test coverage, real-time monitoring, and strong continuous integration pipelines to prevent bugs from reaching production.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Customers may also find software that is constantly changing creates a learning curve which can negatively affect their experience.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Moving to continuous delivery is also a culture shift for developers who are accustomed to traditional release cycles, often requiring a proven DevOps process.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] Adopting this process requires collaboration among multiple stakeholders, including development teams, leadership, operations, and quality assurance.
[src:deployment-strategies/continuous-deployment] In an environment in which data-centric microservices provide the functionality, and where the microservices can have multiple instances, continuous deployment consists of instantiating the new version of a microservice and retiring the old version once it has drained all the requests in flight.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment manages a set of Pods to run an application workload, usually one that doesn't maintain state.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A *Deployment* provides declarative updates for Pods and ReplicaSets.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You describe a *desired state* in a Deployment, and the Deployment Controller changes the actual state to the desired state at a controlled rate.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can define Deployments to create new ReplicaSets, or to remove existing Deployments and adopt all their resources with new Deployments.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Do not manage ReplicaSets owned by a Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Consider opening an issue in the main Kubernetes repository if your use case is not covered below.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The following is an example of a Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Before you begin, make sure your Kubernetes cluster is up and running.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Waiting for rollout to finish: 2 out of 3 new replicas have been updated...
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Run the `kubectl get deployments` again a few seconds later.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to this:Notice that the Deployment has created all three replicas, and all replicas are up-to-date (they contain the latest Pod template) and available.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] To see the ReplicaSet (`rs`) created by the Deployment, run `kubectl get rs`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to this:ReplicaSet output shows the following fields:Notice that the name of the ReplicaSet is always formatted as `[DEPLOYMENT-NAME]-[HASH]`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This name will become the basis for the Pods which are created.The `HASH` string is the same as the `pod-template-hash` label on the ReplicaSet.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] To see the labels automatically generated for each Pod, run `kubectl get pods --show-labels`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The output is similar to:The created ReplicaSet ensures that there are three `nginx` Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You must specify an appropriate selector and Pod template labels in a Deployment (in this case, `app: nginx`).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Do not overlap labels or selectors with other controllers (including other Deployments and StatefulSets).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Kubernetes doesn't stop you from overlapping, and if multiple controllers have overlapping selectors those controllers might conflict and behave unexpectedly.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The `pod-template-hash` label is added by the Deployment controller to every ReplicaSet that a Deployment creates or adopts.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This label ensures that child ReplicaSets of a Deployment do not overlap.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] It is generated by hashing the `PodTemplate` of the ReplicaSet and using the resulting hash as the label value that is added to the ReplicaSet selector, Pod template labels, and in any existing Pods that the ReplicaSet might have.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] ) is changed, for example if the labels or container images of the template are updated.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Other updates, such as scaling the Deployment, do not trigger a rollout.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Each time a new Deployment is observed by the Deployment controller, a ReplicaSet is created to bring up the desired Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If the Deployment is updated, the existing ReplicaSet that controls Pods whose labels match `.spec.selector` but whose template does not match `.spec.template` is scaled down.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Eventually, the new ReplicaSet is scaled to `.spec.replicas` and all old ReplicaSets is scaled to 0.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you update a Deployment while an existing rollout is in progress, the Deployment creates a new ReplicaSet as per the update and start scaling that up, and rolls over the ReplicaSet that it was scaling up previously -- it will add it to its list of old ReplicaSets and start scaling it down.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, suppose you create a Deployment to create 5 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2`, but then update the Deployment to create 5 replicas of `nginx:1.16.1`, when only 3 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2` had been created.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] In that case, the Deployment immediately starts killing the 3 `nginx:1.14.2` Pods that it had created, and starts creating `nginx:1.16.1` Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] It does not wait for the 5 replicas of `nginx:1.14.2` to be created before changing course.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] It is generally discouraged to make label selector updates and it is suggested to plan your selectors up front.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment's label selector is **immutable** after creation; it cannot be updated via `kubectl patch`, `kubectl edit`, `kubectl apply`, or tools like `helm upgrade`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you must change the selector, you have to delete the Deployment and recreate it.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] By default, deleting the Deployment also deletes its running Pods, causing downtime; use `--cascade=orphan` if you need those Pods to keep running while you recreate the Deployment (see the implications below).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Sometimes, you may want to rollback a Deployment; for example, when the Deployment is not stable, such as crash looping.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] By default, all of the Deployment's rollout history is kept in the system so that you can rollback anytime you want (you can change that by modifying revision history limit).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment's revision is created when a Deployment's rollout is triggered.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] ) is changed, for example if you update the labels or container images of the template.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Other updates, such as scaling the Deployment, do not create a Deployment revision, so that you can facilitate simultaneous manual- or auto-scaling.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This means that when you roll back to an earlier revision, only the Deployment's Pod template part is rolled back.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Waiting for rollout to finish: 1 out of 3 new replicas have been updated...
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Follow the steps given below to rollback the Deployment from the current version to the previous version, which is version 2.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Assuming horizontal Pod autoscaling is enabled in your cluster, you can set up an autoscaler for your Deployment and choose the minimum and maximum number of Pods you want to run based on the CPU utilization of your existing Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] RollingUpdate Deployments support running multiple versions of an application at the same time.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] When you or an autoscaler scales a RollingUpdate Deployment that is in the middle of a rollout (either in progress or paused), the Deployment controller balances the additional replicas in the existing active ReplicaSets (ReplicaSets with Pods) in order to mitigate risk.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, you are running a Deployment with 10 replicas, maxSurge=3, and maxUnavailable=2.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] In our example above, 3 replicas are added to the old ReplicaSet and 2 replicas are added to the new ReplicaSet.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The rollout process should eventually move all replicas to the new ReplicaSet, assuming the new replicas become healthy.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The rollout status confirms how the replicas were added to each ReplicaSet.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] When you update a Deployment, or plan to, you can pause rollouts for that Deployment before you trigger one or more updates.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] When you're ready to apply those changes, you resume rollouts for the Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This approach allows you to apply multiple fixes in between pausing and resuming without triggering unnecessary rollouts.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You cannot rollback a paused Deployment until you resume it.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] A Deployment enters various states during its lifecycle.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] It can be progressing while rolling out a new ReplicaSet, it can be complete, or it can fail to progress.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can monitor the progress for a Deployment by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This `Progressing` condition will retain a status value of `"True"` until a new rollout is initiated.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The condition holds even when availability of replicas changes (which does instead affect the `Available` condition).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can check if a Deployment has completed by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If the rollout completed successfully, `kubectl rollout status` returns a zero exit code.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Your Deployment may get stuck trying to deploy its newest ReplicaSet without ever completing.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] One way you can detect this condition is to specify a deadline parameter in your Deployment spec: (`.spec.progressDeadlineSeconds`).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] `.spec.progressDeadlineSeconds` denotes the number of seconds the Deployment controller waits before indicating (in the Deployment status) that the Deployment progress has stalled.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] This condition can also fail early and is then set to status value of `"False"` due to reasons as `ReplicaSetCreateError`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Also, the deadline is not taken into account anymore once the Deployment rollout completes.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] See the Kubernetes API conventions for more information on status conditions.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Higher level orchestrators can take advantage of it and act accordingly, for example, rollback the Deployment to its previous version.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you pause a Deployment rollout, Kubernetes does not check progress against your specified deadline.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can safely pause a Deployment rollout in the middle of a rollout and resume without triggering the condition for exceeding the deadline.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You may experience transient errors with your Deployments, either due to a low timeout that you have set or due to any other kind of error that can be treated as transient.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, let's suppose you have insufficient quota.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can address an issue of insufficient quota by scaling down your Deployment, by scaling down other controllers you may be running, or by increasing quota in your namespace.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you satisfy the quota conditions and the Deployment controller then completes the Deployment rollout, you'll see the Deployment's status update with a successful condition (`status: "True"` and `reason: NewReplicaSetAvailable`).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] `type: Available` with `status: "True"` means that your Deployment has minimum availability.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Minimum availability is dictated by the parameters specified in the deployment strategy.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can check if a Deployment has failed to progress by using `kubectl rollout status`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] `kubectl rollout status` returns a non-zero exit code if the Deployment has exceeded the progression deadline.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] All actions that apply to a complete Deployment also apply to a failed Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can scale it up/down, roll back to a previous revision, or even pause it if you need to apply multiple tweaks in the Deployment Pod template.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] You can set `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` field in a Deployment to specify how many old ReplicaSets for this Deployment you want to retain.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The rest will be garbage-collected in the background.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Explicitly setting this field to 0, will result in cleaning up all the history of your Deployment thus that Deployment will not be able to roll back.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] The cleanup only starts **after** a Deployment reaches a complete state.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you set `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` to 0, any rollout nonetheless triggers creation of a new ReplicaSet before Kubernetes removes the old one.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] Even with a non-zero revision history limit, you can have more ReplicaSets than the limit you configure.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] For example, if pods are crash looping, and there are multiple rolling updates events triggered over time, you might end up with more ReplicaSets than the `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` because the Deployment never reaches a complete state.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p01] If you want to roll out releases to a subset of users or servers using the Deployment, you can create multiple Deployments, one for each release, following the canary pattern described in managing resources.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] As with all other Kubernetes configs, a Deployment needs `.apiVersion`, `.kind`, and `.metadata` fields.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For general information about working with config files, see deploying applications, configuring containers, and using kubectl to manage resources documents.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] When the control plane creates new Pods for a Deployment, the `.metadata.name` of the Deployment is part of the basis for naming those Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The name of a Deployment must be a valid DNS subdomain value, but this can produce unexpected results for the Pod hostnames.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For best compatibility, the name should follow the more restrictive rules for a DNS label.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment also needs a `.spec` section.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The `.spec.template` and `.spec.selector` are the only required fields of the `.spec`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] It has exactly the same schema as a Pod, except it is nested and does not have an `apiVersion` or `kind`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] In addition to required fields for a Pod, a Pod template in a Deployment must specify appropriate labels and an appropriate restart policy.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For labels, make sure not to overlap with other controllers.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Only a `.spec.template.spec.restartPolicy` equal to `Always` is allowed, which is the default if not specified.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.replicas` is an optional field that specifies the number of desired Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If a HorizontalPodAutoscaler (or any similar API for horizontal scaling) is managing scaling for a Deployment, don't set `.spec.replicas`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Instead, allow the Kubernetes control plane to manage the `.spec.replicas` field automatically.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.selector` is a required field that specifies a label selector for the Pods targeted by this Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.selector` must match `.spec.template.metadata.labels`, or it will be rejected by the API.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] In API version `apps/v1`, `.spec.selector` and `.metadata.labels` do not default to `.spec.template.metadata.labels` if not set.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Also note that `.spec.selector` is immutable after creation of the Deployment in `apps/v1`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment may terminate Pods whose labels match the selector if their template is different from `.spec.template` or if the total number of such Pods exceeds `.spec.replicas`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] It brings up new Pods with `.spec.template` if the number of Pods is less than the desired number.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] You should not create other Pods whose labels match this selector, either directly, by creating another Deployment, or by creating another controller such as a ReplicaSet or a ReplicationController.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If you do so, the first Deployment thinks that it created these other Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Kubernetes does not stop you from doing this.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If you have multiple controllers that have overlapping selectors, the controllers will fight with each other and won't behave correctly.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy` specifies the strategy used to replace old Pods by new ones.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.type` can be "Recreate" or "RollingUpdate".
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] All existing Pods are killed before new ones are created when `.spec.strategy.type==Recreate`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] This will only guarantee Pod termination previous to creation for upgrades.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If you upgrade a Deployment, all Pods of the old revision will be terminated immediately.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Successful removal is awaited before any Pod of the new revision is created.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If you manually delete a Pod, the lifecycle is controlled by the ReplicaSet and the replacement will be created immediately (even if the old Pod is still in a Terminating state).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The Deployment updates Pods in a rolling update fashion (gradually scale down the old ReplicaSets and scale up the new one) when `.spec.strategy.type==RollingUpdate`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] You can specify `maxUnavailable` and `maxSurge` to control the rolling update process.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxUnavailable` is an optional field that specifies the maximum number of Pods that can be unavailable during the update process.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The value can be an absolute number (for example, 5) or a percentage of desired Pods (for example, 10%).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The absolute number is calculated from percentage by rounding down.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The value cannot be 0 if `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxSurge` is 0.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For example, when this value is set to 30%, the old ReplicaSet can be scaled down to 70% of desired Pods immediately when the rolling update starts.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Once new Pods are ready, old ReplicaSet can be scaled down further, followed by scaling up the new ReplicaSet, ensuring that the total number of Pods available at all times during the update is at least 70% of the desired Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxSurge` is an optional field that specifies the maximum number of Pods that can be created over the desired number of Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The value cannot be 0 if `maxUnavailable` is 0.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The absolute number is calculated from the percentage by rounding up.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] For example, when this value is set to 30%, the new ReplicaSet can be scaled up immediately when the rolling update starts, such that the total number of old and new Pods does not exceed 130% of desired Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Once old Pods have been killed, the new ReplicaSet can be scaled up further, ensuring that the total number of Pods running at any time during the update is at most 130% of desired Pods.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The Deployment controller will keep retrying the Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] If specified, this field needs to be greater than `.spec.minReadySeconds`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.minReadySeconds` is an optional field that specifies the minimum number of seconds for which a newly created Pod should be ready without any of its containers crashing, for it to be considered available.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] This defaults to 0 (the Pod will be considered available as soon as it is ready).
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] To learn more about when a Pod is considered ready, see Container Probes.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Pods that become terminating due to deletion or scale down may take a long time to terminate, and may consume additional resources during that period.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] As a result, the total number of all pods can temporarily exceed `.spec.replicas`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] Terminating pods can be tracked using the `.status.terminatingReplicas` field of the Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment's revision history is stored in the ReplicaSets it controls.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.revisionHistoryLimit` is an optional field that specifies the number of old ReplicaSets to retain to allow rollback.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] These old ReplicaSets consume resources in `etcd` and crowd the output of `kubectl get rs`.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The configuration of each Deployment revision is stored in its ReplicaSets; therefore, once an old ReplicaSet is deleted, you lose the ability to rollback to that revision of Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] By default, 10 old ReplicaSets will be kept, however its ideal value depends on the frequency and stability of new Deployments.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] More specifically, setting this field to zero means that all old ReplicaSets with 0 replicas will be cleaned up.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] In this case, a new Deployment rollout cannot be undone, since its revision history is cleaned up.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] `.spec.paused` is an optional boolean field for pausing and resuming a Deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] The only difference between a paused Deployment and one that is not paused, is that any changes into the PodTemplateSpec of the paused Deployment will not trigger new rollouts as long as it is paused.
[src:deployment-strategies/controllers-deployment-p02] A Deployment is not paused by default when it is created.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] In software deployment, an **environment** or **tier** is a computer system or set of systems in which a computer program or software component is deployed and executed.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] This structured release management process allows phased deployment (rollout), testing, and rollback in case of problems.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Environments may vary significantly in size: the development environment is typically an individual developer's workstation, while the production environment may be a network of many geographically distributed machines in data centers, or virtual machines in cloud computing.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Code, data, and configuration may be deployed in parallel, and need not connect to the corresponding tier—for example, pre-production code might connect to a production database.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Deployment architectures vary significantly, but, broadly, the tiers are bookended by starting at *development* (DEV) and ending at *production* (PROD).
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] A common 4-tier architecture is *development, testing, model, production* (DEV, TEST, MODL, PROD), with software being deployed to each in order.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Other common environments include Quality Control (QC), for acceptance testing; sandbox or experimental (EXP), for experiments that are not intended to proceed to production; and Disaster Recovery, to provide an immediate fallback in case of problems with production.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Another common architecture is development, testing, acceptance and production (DTAP).
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] This language is particularly suited for server programs, where servers run in a remote data center; for code that runs on an end user's device, such as applications (apps) or clients, one can refer to the user environment (USER) or local environment (LOCAL) instead.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Exact definitions and boundaries between environments vary – test may be considered part of dev, Acceptance may be considered part of test, part of stage, or be separate, etc.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] The main tiers are progressed through in order, with new releases being deployed (*rolled out* or *pushed*) to each in turn.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Experimental and recovery tiers, if present, are outside this flow – experimental releases are terminal, while recovery is typically an old or duplicate version of production, deployed after production.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] In case of problems, one can *roll back* to the old release, most simply by pushing the old release as if it were a new release.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] The last step, deploying to production ("pushing to prod") is the most sensitive, as any problems result in immediate user impact.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] For this is often handled differently, at least being monitored more carefully, and in some cases having phased rollout or only requiring flipping a switch, allowing rapid rollback.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] It is best to avoid a name like Quality Assurance (QA); QA doesn’t mean software testing.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Testing is important, but it is different from QA.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Sometimes deployment is done outside of this regular process, primarily to provide urgent or relatively minor changes, without requiring a full release.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] This may consist of a single patch, a large service pack, or a small hotfix.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] The table below describes a finely-divided list of tiers.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] The development environment (dev) is the environment in which changes to software are developed, most simply an individual developer's workstation.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] The environment on an individual workstation, in which changes are worked on and tried out, may be referred to as the *local environment* or a sandbox.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] The purpose of the test environment is to allow human testers to exercise new and changed code via either automated checks or non-automated techniques.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] After the developer accepts the new code and configurations through unit testing in the development environment, the items are moved to one or more test environments.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Upon test failure, the test environment can remove the faulty code from the test platforms, contact the responsible developer, and provide detailed test and result logs.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] If all tests pass, the test environment or a continuous integration framework controlling the tests can automatically promote the code to the next deployment environment.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Different types of testing suggest different types of test environments, some or all of which may be virtualized to allow rapid, parallel testing to take place.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] For example, automated user interface tests may occur across several virtual operating systems and displays (real or virtual).
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Performance tests may require a normalized physical baseline hardware configuration, so that performance test results can be compared over time.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Availability or durability testing may depend on failure simulators in virtual hardware and virtual networks.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Tests may be serial (one after the other) or parallel (some or all at once) depending on the sophistication of the test environment.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] A significant goal for agile and other high-productivity software development practices is reducing the time from software design or specification to delivery in production.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Highly automated and parallelized test environments are important contributors to rapid software development.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] A stage, staging or pre-production environment is an environment for testing that exactly resembles a production environment.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] It seeks to mirror an actual production environment as closely as possible and may connect to other production services and data, such as databases.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] For example, servers will be run on remote machines, rather than locally (as on a developer's workstation during dev, or on a single test machine during the test), which tests the effects of networking on the system.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] The primary use of a staging environment is to test all the installation/configuration/migration scripts and procedures before they're applied to a production environment.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] This ensures all major and minor upgrades to a production environment are completed reliably, without errors, and in a minimum of time.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Another important use of staging is performance testing, particularly load testing, as this is often sensitive to the environment.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Staging is also used by some organizations to preview new features to select customers or to validate integrations with live versions of external dependencies.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] The production environment is also known as *live*, particularly for servers, as it is the environment that users directly interact with.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Deploying to production is the most sensitive step; it may be done by deploying new code directly (overwriting old code, so only one copy is present at a time), or by deploying a configuration change.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] These in turn may be done all at once or gradually, in phases.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] When deploying a new release to production, rather than immediately deploying to all instances or users, it may be deployed to a single instance or fraction of users first, and then either deployed to all or gradually deployed in phases, in order to catch any last-minute problems.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] This is similar to staging, except actually done in production, and is referred to as a *canary release*, by analogy with coal mining.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] This adds complexity due to multiple releases being run simultaneously, and is thus usually over quickly, to avoid compatibility problems.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Development, Staging and Production are known and documented environment variables in ASP.NET Core.
[src:deployment-strategies/deployment-environment] Depending on the defined variable, different code is executed and content rendered, and different security and debug settings are applied.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:deployment-strategies/high-availability] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
[src:deployment-strategies/rolling-release] A rolling release model is different from a staged or "staggered" rollout, in which an update is gradually made available to an increasing percentage of users for testing or bandwidth reasons.
[src:deployment-strategies/rolling-release] An example of a rolling release would be Arch Linux, where new packages and updates roll in constantly, and significant changes to the distribution may occur at any time by the developers.
[src:deployment-strategies/rolling-release] This is in contrast to Ubuntu Linux, which has biannual releases, with the only major changes after a release being security updates or significant bug fixes.
[src:deployment-strategies/rolling-release] Rolling release development models are one of many types of software release life cycles.
[src:deployment-strategies/rolling-release] Some modern Distributed SQL databases such as YugabyteDB also support this feature.
[src:deployment-strategies/rolling-release] A rolling release is typically implemented using small and frequent updates.
[src:deployment-strategies/rolling-release] However, simply having updates does not automatically mean that a piece of software is using a rolling release cycle; for this, the philosophy of developers must be to work with one code branch as opposed to discrete versions.
[src:deployment-strategies/rolling-release] When the rolling release is employed as the development model, software updates are typically delivered to users by a package manager on the user's personal computer, accessing through the internet a remote software repository (often via a download mirror) stored on an internet file server.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] and transfer to the computer system(s) on which it will be run in production.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] required for the system to operate with tolerable performance and planning and/or documenting subsequent activities of the deployment process.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] for executing the software (manually or automatically).
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] and/or making all the required subsystems ready to use.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] , the main copy of the software to be used by users - "production" - might be installed on a production server in a production environment.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The **software release life cycle** is the process of developing, testing, and distributing a software product (e.g., an operating system).
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] It typically consists of several stages, such as pre-alpha, alpha, beta, and release candidate, before the final version, or "gold", is released to the public.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Pre-alpha refers to the early stages of development, when the software is still being designed and built.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha testing is the first phase of formal testing, during which the software is tested internally using white-box techniques.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Beta testing is the next phase, in which the software is tested by a larger group of users, typically outside the organization that developed it.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The beta phase is focused on reducing impacts on users and may include usability testing.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] After beta testing, the software may go through one or more release candidate phases, in which it is refined and tested further, before the final version is released.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Some software, particularly in the internet and technology industries, is released in a perpetual beta state, meaning that it is continuously being updated and improved, and is never considered to be a fully completed product.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] This approach allows for a more agile development process and enables the software to be released and used by users earlier in the development cycle.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Pre-alpha refers to all activities performed during the software project before formal testing.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] These activities can include requirements analysis, software design, software development, and unit testing.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In typical open source development, there are several types of pre-alpha versions.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] *Milestone* versions include specific sets of functions and are released as soon as the feature is complete.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The alpha phase of the release life cycle is the first phase of software testing (alpha is the first letter of the Greek alphabet, used as the number 1).
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In this phase, developers generally test the software using white-box techniques.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Additional validation is then performed using black-box or gray-box techniques, by another testing team.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Moving to black-box testing inside the organization is known as *alpha release*.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software is not thoroughly tested by the developer before it is released to customers.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software may contain serious errors, and any resulting instability could cause crashes or data loss.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software may not contain all of the features that are planned for the final version.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In general, external availability of alpha software is uncommon for proprietary software, while open source software often has publicly available alpha versions.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The alpha phase usually ends with a feature freeze, indicating that no more features will be added to the software.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] At this time, the software is said to be feature-complete.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A beta test is carried out following acceptance testing at the supplier's site (the alpha test) and immediately before the general release of the software as a product.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A **feature-complete** (FC) version of a piece of software has all of its planned or primary features implemented but is not yet final due to bugs, performance or stability issues.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] This occurs at the end of alpha testing in development.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Usually, feature-complete software still has to undergo beta testing and bug fixing, as well as performance or stability enhancement before it can go to release candidate, and finally gold status.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Beta, named after the second letter of the Greek alphabet, is the software development phase following alpha.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A beta phase generally begins when the software is feature-complete but likely to contain several known or unknown bugs.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Software in the beta phase will generally have many more bugs in it than completed software and speed or performance issues, and may still cause crashes or data loss.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The focus of beta testing is reducing impacts on users, often incorporating usability testing.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The process of delivering a beta version to the users is called *beta release* and is typically the first time that the software is available outside the organization that developed it.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Software beta releases can be either open or closed, depending on whether they are openly available or only available to a limited audience.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Beta version software is often useful for demonstrations and previews within an organization and to prospective customers.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Some developers refer to this stage as a *preview*, *preview release*, *prototype*, *technical preview* or *technology preview* (*TP*).
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Some software is kept in so-called *perpetual beta*, where new features are continually added to the software without establishing a final "stable" release.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] As the Internet has facilitated the rapid and inexpensive distribution of software, companies have begun to take a looser approach to the use of the word *beta*.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A *release candidate* (*RC*), also known as gamma testing or "going silver", is a beta version with the potential to be a stable product, which is ready to release unless significant bugs emerge.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In this stage of product stabilization, all product features have been designed, coded, and tested through one or more beta cycles with no known showstopper-class bugs.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A release is called *code complete* when the development team agrees that no entirely new source code will be added to this release.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] There could still be source code changes to fix defects, changes to documentation and data files, and peripheral code for test cases or utilities.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Also called *production release*, the *stable release* is the last *release candidate* (*RC*) which has passed all stages of verification and tests.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Any known remaining bugs are considered acceptable.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Linux distributions like Debian) also have *long-term support* (*LTS*) releases which are based on full releases that have already been tried and tested and receive only security updates.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Once released, the software is generally known as a "stable release".
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The formal term often depends on the method of release: physical media, online release, or a web application.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Usually the released software is assigned an official version name or version number.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] (Pre-release software may or may not have a separate internal project code name or internal version number).
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The term "release to manufacturing" (RTM), also known as "going gold", is a term used when a software product is ready to be delivered.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] This build may be digitally signed, allowing the end user to verify the integrity and authenticity of the software purchase.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The RTM build is known as the "gold master" or GM is sent for mass duplication or disc replication if applicable.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The terminology is taken from the audio record-making industry, specifically the process of mastering.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] RTM precedes general availability (GA) when the product is released to the public.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] A golden master build (GM) is typically the final build of a piece of software in the beta stages for developers.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Typically, for iOS, it is the final build before a major release, however, there have been a few exceptions.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] RTM could also mean in other contexts that the software has been delivered or released to a client or customer for installation or distribution to the related hardware end user computers or machines.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The term does *not* define the delivery mechanism or volume; it only states that the quality is sufficient for mass distribution.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The deliverable from the engineering organization is frequently in the form of a golden master media used for duplication or to produce the image for the web.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] During its supported lifetime, the software is sometimes subjected to service releases, patches or service packs, sometimes also called "interim releases" or "maintenance releases" (MR).
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] For example, Microsoft released three major service packs for the 32-bit editions of Windows XP and two service packs for the 64-bit editions.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Such service releases contain a collection of updates, fixes, and enhancements, delivered in the form of a single installable package.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Some software is released with the expectation of regular support.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Classes of software that generally involve protracted support as the norm include anti-virus suites and massively multiplayer online games.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Continuing with this Windows XP example, Microsoft did offer paid updates for five more years after the end of extended support.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] This means that support ended on April 8, 2019.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] After the end-of-life date, the developer will usually not implement any new features, fix existing defects, bugs, or vulnerabilities (whether known before that date or not), or provide any support for the product.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] If the developer wishes, they may release the source code, so that the platform may be maintained by volunteers.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Usage of the "alpha/beta" test terminology originated at IBM.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Similar terminologies for IBM's software development were used by people involved with IBM from at least the 1950s (and probably earlier).
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] "A" test was the verification of a new product before the public announcement.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The "B" test was the verification before releasing the product to be manufactured.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The "C" test was the final test before the general availability of the product.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] As software became a significant part of IBM's offerings, the alpha test terminology was used to denote the pre-announcement test and the beta test was used to show product readiness for general availability.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Martin Belsky, a manager on some of IBM's earlier software projects claimed to have invented the terminology.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] IBM dropped the alpha/beta terminology during the 1960s, but by then it had received fairly wide notice.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] The usage of "beta test" to refer to testing done by customers was not done in IBM.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Major public betas developed afterward, with early customers having purchased a "pioneer edition" of the WordVision word processor for the IBM PC for $49.95.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In 1984, Stephen Manes wrote that "in a brilliant marketing coup, Bruce and James Program Publishers managed to get people to *pay* for the privilege of testing the product." In September 2000, a *boxed version* of Apple's Mac OS X Public Beta operating system was released.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Between September 2005 and May 2006, Microsoft released *community technology preview*s (*CTP*s) for Windows Vista.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] From 2009 to 2011, *Minecraft* was in public beta.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] In February 2005, ZDNet published an article about the phenomenon of a beta version often staying for years and being used as if it were at the production level.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] It noted that Gmail and Google News, for example, had been in beta for a long time although widely used; Google News left beta in January 2006, followed by Google Apps (now named Google Workspace), including Gmail, in July 2009.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] Since the introduction of Windows 8, Microsoft has called pre-release software a *preview* rather than *beta*.
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] All pre-release builds released through the Windows Insider Program launched in 2014 are termed "Insider Preview builds".
[src:deployment-strategies/software-release-life-cycle] "Beta" may also indicate something more like a release candidate, or as a form of time-limited demo, or marketing technique.
